                    />

            
    
<figcaption class="attribution">
    
    
    
    </figcaption>

</figure>

        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="28.0">Pull any remaining profits before regulators hit you with violations and fines for your remaining wells that aren’t pumping and may be leaking.</p>
        
    
                    

<figure
    data-pp-id="29"
    data-pp-blocktype="image"
    class="bb-image size08 center  wide-sm wrap 
                ">

    


                    
    


    <img
        class=""
        alt=""
        width="2000"
        height="1597"
        loading="lazy" js-autosizes        src="https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20241224-oil-arkle-06-hahaha.png?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=639&amp;q=80&amp;w=800&amp;s=452bbb43b8507b2ad5af9c58b42f6438"
        srcset="https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20241224-oil-arkle-06-hahaha.png?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=319&amp;q=80&amp;w=400&amp;s=f44b5ba0f8b801cec03221383ad6fd57 400w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20241224-oil-arkle-06-hahaha.png?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=639&amp;q=80&amp;w=800&amp;s=452bbb43b8507b2ad5af9c58b42f6438 800w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20241224-oil-arkle-06-hahaha.png?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=958&amp;q=80&amp;w=1200&amp;s=f6f1e953dac259ec3365922d9464e275 1200w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20241224-oil-arkle-06-hahaha.png?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=1038&amp;q=80&amp;w=1300&amp;s=6636ce4dd9d9a5ecbc7aed187cbb2788 1300w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20241224-oil-arkle-06-hahaha.png?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=1158&amp;q=80&amp;w=1450&amp;s=6a28cd00349366e92ccf04595e31058a 1450w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20241224-oil-arkle-06-hahaha.png?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=1278&amp;q=80&amp;w=1600&amp;s=be641b73d7e1424b82e4863f653e2a29 1600w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20241224-oil-arkle-06-hahaha.png?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=1597&amp;q=80&amp;w=2000&amp;s=24291d4a38f3326899b08d60c57eae60 2000w"
                    />

            
    
<figcaption class="attribution">
    
    
    
    </figcaption>

</figure>

        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="30.0">Then, idle the wells — pausing production, but not plugging them or cleaning up — and walk away. Regulators are typically tasked with ensuring that as much oil as possible is pumped out of the ground, so rules allow wells to sit idle, instead of being plugged, in case prices surge and it becomes profitable to restart them. However, <a href="https://www.latimes.com/projects/california-oil-well-drilling-idle-cleanup/">a study in California found that</a>, after wells are inactive for only 10 months, there’s a 50-50 chance they will never produce again.</p>
        
    
                    

<figure
    data-pp-id="31"
    data-pp-blocktype="image"
    class="bb-image size08 center  wide-sm wrap 
                ">

    


                    
    


    <img
        class=""
        alt=""
        width="2000"
        height="1909"
        loading="lazy" js-autosizes        src="https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20241224-oil-arkle-06-idle.png?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=764&amp;q=80&amp;w=800&amp;s=a0bcf4406e6054665974e8af8d63dadb"
