                    />

            
    
<figcaption class="attribution">
    
    
    
    </figcaption>

</figure>

        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="52.0">In reality, Siana is the corporate shield for a man named Tom Ragsdale. After he aggregated his few wells, he generated cash through a trickle of oil and gas production and set up a business injecting other companies’ wastewater into his wells to dispose of it. But the state worried that Ragsdale’s operations were polluting the environment and that he was refusing to pay royalties and rental fees he owed the state, according to State Land Office staff.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="53.0">Ragsdale did not respond to repeated requests for comment from ProPublica and Capital &amp; Main. He also did not appear for a pretrial conference <a href="https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/25444494-2016-04-27-complaint-for-damages/">after the state brought legal action against Siana</a>, <a href="https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/25141647-2020-09-01-judgment/?q=appear+and+meaningfully&amp;mode=document#document/p2">court records show</a>, and a state court judge ruled against his companies.</p>
        
    
                    

<figure
    data-pp-id="54"
    data-pp-blocktype="image"
    class="bb-image size08 center  wide-sm wrap 
                ">

    


                    
    


    <img
        class=""
        alt=""
        width="2000"
        height="1680"
        loading="lazy" js-autosizes        src="https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20241224-oil-arkle-08-Ragsdale.png?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=672&amp;q=80&amp;w=800&amp;s=070b476588bb56c9e4d5a15d5efa6a9f"
        srcset="https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20241224-oil-arkle-08-Ragsdale.png?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=336&amp;q=80&amp;w=400&amp;s=838bdf4b9271523cc770e40cfa477c58 400w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20241224-oil-arkle-08-Ragsdale.png?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=672&amp;q=80&amp;w=800&amp;s=070b476588bb56c9e4d5a15d5efa6a9f 800w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20241224-oil-arkle-08-Ragsdale.png?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=1008&amp;q=80&amp;w=1200&amp;s=b5813db577d6e882cf0e07e0148e29fc 1200w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20241224-oil-arkle-08-Ragsdale.png?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=1092&amp;q=80&amp;w=1300&amp;s=8f38e82f7ab951a21d356a651c543af0 1300w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20241224-oil-arkle-08-Ragsdale.png?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=1218&amp;q=80&amp;w=1450&amp;s=f7f5bf8b35f32a978c050fa3e9c552f1 1450w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20241224-oil-arkle-08-Ragsdale.png?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=1344&amp;q=80&amp;w=1600&amp;s=48a679a86ea48eb531eb1119634dd3df 1600w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20241224-oil-arkle-08-Ragsdale.png?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=1680&amp;q=80&amp;w=2000&amp;s=0a393688f5f2c2b3498ccf2e1a5e00cf 2000w"
                    />

            
    
<figcaption class="attribution">
    
    
    
    </figcaption>

</figure>

        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="55.0">Siana was responsible for at least 16 spills, <a href="https://wwwapps.emnrd.nm.gov/OCD/OCDPermitting/Data/Spills/SpillSearchResults.aspx?IncidentIdSearchClause=BeginsWith&amp;Severity=All&amp;Ogrid_Name=siana&amp;OperatorSearchClause=BeginsWith&amp;FacilityIdSearchClause=BeginsWith&amp;FacilityNameSearchClause=BeginsWith&amp;WellNameSearchClause=BeginsWith&amp;Section=00">according to New Mexico Oil Conservation Division data</a>, mainly spilling what’s called produced water, a briny wastewater that comes to the surface alongside oil and gas. “Corrosion” and “Equipment Failure” were among the causes.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="56.0">The State Land Office hired an engineering firm to study the damage. The firm produced <a href="https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/25141650-2018-07-05-siana-tank-battery-and-swd-well-site-contamination-report-rev">a damning 201-page report in 2018</a>, finding oil and salt contamination exceeding state limits at Siana’s most polluted site. At high enough levels, these substances can kill plants, harm wildlife and impact human health.</p>
        
    
                    

<figure
    data-pp-id="57"
    data-pp-blocktype="image"
    class="bb-image size08 center  wide-sm wrap 
                ">

    


                    
    


    <img
        class=""
        alt=""
        width="2000"
        height="1573"
        loading="lazy" js-autosizes        src="https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20241224-oil-arkle-09-siana-well01.png?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=629&amp;q=80&amp;w=800&amp;s=69448376ce861c43cf5a0fa936df02bc"
